## 9. Algorithm Comparison Summary <a name="comparison"></a>

### Complexity at a Glance

| Algorithm | Best | Average | Worst | Space | Stable | In-place |
|-----------|------|---------|-------|-------|--------|---------|
| Bubble Sort | O(n) | O(n²) | O(n²) | O(1) | Yes | Yes |
| Selection Sort | O(n²) | O(n²) | O(n²) | O(1) | No | Yes |
| Insertion Sort | O(n) | O(n²) | O(n²) | O(1) | Yes | Yes |
| Merge Sort | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n) | Yes | No |
| Quick Sort | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n²) | O(log n) | No | Yes |
| Heap Sort | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(1) | No | Yes |
| Counting Sort | O(n+k) | O(n+k) | O(n+k) | O(n+k) | Yes | No |
| Radix Sort | O(d(n+b)) | O(d(n+b)) | O(d(n+b)) | O(n+b) | Yes | No |

### When to Use Each Algorithm

```
Data size SMALL (n < ~20):
  → Insertion Sort       (low overhead, fast in practice, great for nearly sorted)

Data size MEDIUM/LARGE, general-purpose:
  → Quick Sort           (fastest in practice due to cache efficiency)
  → Merge Sort           (when stability is required, or sorting linked lists)

Worst-case guarantee required, O(1) space:
  → Heap Sort            (guaranteed O(n log n), no extra memory)

Integers with small value range (k ≈ n):
  → Counting Sort        (linear time, dead simple)

Multi-digit integers, fixed-width keys:
  → Radix Sort           (linear time, handles large ranges unlike Counting Sort)

Nearly sorted data:
  → Insertion Sort       (degrades gracefully, O(n) on already-sorted input)
  → Bubble Sort          (with early-exit optimization)

Memory is extremely limited:
  → Heap Sort            (O(1) space, O(n log n) guaranteed)

External sorting (data too large for RAM):
  → Merge Sort           (naturally supports external merge patterns)
```

### All Algorithms on `[64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]` — Result Verification

```python
import random

algorithms = {
    "Bubble Sort":    bubble_sort,
    "Selection Sort": selection_sort,
    "Insertion Sort": insertion_sort,
    "Merge Sort":     merge_sort,
    "Quick Sort":     quick_sort,
    "Heap Sort":      heap_sort,
    "Counting Sort":  counting_sort,
    "Radix Sort":     radix_sort,
}

data = [64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]
expected = [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]

for name, fn in algorithms.items():
    result = fn(data.copy())
    status = "PASS" if result == expected else "FAIL"
    print(f"  [{status}] {name}: {result}")
```

