### Key Conceptual Takeaways

| Concept | Algorithms |
|---------|-----------|
| **Divide & Conquer** | Merge Sort, Quick Sort |
| **Comparison-based** (O(n log n) lower bound) | Bubble, Selection, Insertion, Merge, Quick, Heap |
| **Non-comparison** (can beat O(n log n)) | Counting Sort, Radix Sort |
| **Adaptive** (faster on nearly-sorted data) | Bubble Sort (w/ early exit), Insertion Sort |
| **Foundation of real-world sorts** | Insertion (Timsort base case), Merge (Timsort merging), Quick (Introsort primary) |

Python's built-in `list.sort()` and `sorted()` use **Timsort** — a hybrid of Merge Sort and Insertion Sort that achieves O(n log n) worst case while exploiting existing order in real-world data. Understanding the eight algorithms above gives you the conceptual foundation to understand why Timsort is designed the way it is.
